        body: "**Pricing Competitive Analysis**\n\nIdentify competitors (5-7 direct):\n- Tier 1: Direct alternatives (same market, same use case)\n- Tier 2: Adjacent alternatives (same market, different use case)\n- Tier 3: Indirect alternatives (different market, similar use case)\n\nExample (CRM market):\n- Tier 1 direct: Salesforce, HubSpot, Pipedrive, Zendesk\n- Tier 2 adjacent: Monday.com (project management CRM), Slack (communication CRM)\n- Tier 3 indirect: Google Sheets (free alternative), Excel (spreadsheet)\n\nMap pricing (tiers + prices):\n\nCompetitor | Tier 1 | Tier 2 | Tier 3 | Enterprise | Annual Discount\n---|---|---|---|---|---\nSalesforce | £60 | £150 | £300 | Custom | 10%\nHubSpot | £50 | £200 | £600 | Custom | 15%\nPipedrive | £14 | £40 | £90 | Custom | 20%\nZendesk | £19 | £49 | £200 | Custom | 15%\nYour company | £30 | £100 | £250 | Custom | 20%\n\nAnalysis:\n- You're priced between Pipedrive (cheap) and Salesforce (expensive)\n- Positioning: \"Enterprise quality at SMB price\"\n- Risk: If customers perceive you = Pipedrive, you're underprice\n- Opportunity: If customers perceive you = Salesforce, you can raise prices\n\n**Competitive Positioning Matrix**\n\n2-axis matrix (pick axes that matter):\n\nExample 1: Price vs. Features\n- X-axis: Price (£0 cheap to £1000+ expensive)\n- Y-axis: Features (basic to comprehensive)\n\nQuadrants:\n- Low price, many features: Pipedrive, HubSpot (value players)\n- High price, many features: Salesforce (premium)\n- Low price, few features: Zendesk (focused)\n- High price, few features: (rarely exists, bad positioning)\n\nExample 2: Price vs. Ease-of-use\n- X-axis: Price\n- Y-axis: Ease (DIY setup to white-glove onboarding)\n\nQuadrants:\n- Low price, easy: Pipedrive (self-serve)\n- High price, easy: Slack (premium + simple)\n- Low price, hard: Excel (free but complex)\n- High price, hard: (rare)\n\nYour positioning:\n- Find white space (gap where no competitor is)\n- Example: All competitors expensive (£50+), you go £20\n- Example: All competitors hard to use, you go \"easy + £100\" (premium for UX)\n- Example: All competitors broad, you go \"focused on SMB + £30\"\n\n**Pricing Strategy Based on Competition**\n\nIf you're behind (more expensive, fewer features):\n- Lower price to compete\n- Example: Competitor £50, you go £35\n- Add differentiator (support, features, speed)\n- Avoid price-only competition (race to bottom)\n\nIf you're ahead (cheaper, more features):\n- Raise price toward competitors\n- Example: You at £30 matching competitor at £80\n- Gradually raise (£30 → £40 → £50) to avoid shock\n- Justify with features/quality\n\nIf you're unique (no direct competitor):\n- Price based on value, not competition\n- Example: New category, no competitors\n- Price 10-20% premium for uniqueness\n- Monitor for when competitors arrive (be ready to defend)\n\n**Competitive Benchmarking Metrics**\n\nCompare yourself to industry:\n\nGrowth rate:\n- SaaS average: 30-50% YoY\n- Market leader: 50%+ (you could be leader)\n- Mature: 10-20% (if growing slower than 20%, losing market share)\n- Your goal: Match or exceed market average\n\nCAC (customer acquisition cost):\n- Low-touch SaaS: £1-3k (self-serve)\n- Mid-market SaaS: £5-15k (sales-driven)\n- Enterprise SaaS: £20-100k+ (executive sales)\n- Benchmark yourself: If CAC 2x higher than peers, you're spending inefficiently\n\nLTV (customer lifetime value):\n- Low-touch: £10-30k (3-5 year lifetime)\n- Mid-market: £50-200k (5-10 year lifetime)\n- Enterprise: £300k+ (8+ year lifetime)\n- CAC payback period: <18 months = healthy\n- LTV:CAC ratio: >3:1 = healthy\n\nNRR (net revenue retention):\n- <100%: Revenue declining (customers leaving faster than growing)\n- 100-105%: Flat (no growth from existing customers)\n- 105-120%: Growing (good expansion)\n- >120%: Excellent (strong expansion)\n- Benchmark: If 90%, you're under-monetizing (competitors 110%)\n\nChurn rate:\n- Good: <3% monthly (healthy)\n- Acceptable: 3-5% monthly (okay)\n- Concerning: 5-10% monthly (high, competitors lower)\n- Critical: >10% monthly (unsustainable)\n- Benchmark: If 8%, and competitors 3%, you have product/GTM issues\n\n**Market Size and TAM Analysis**\n\nWhere can you grow?\n\nTotal addressable market (TAM):\n- Ask: How many potential customers in world?\n- Example (CRM): 1M companies that use CRM = £1B TAM at £1000 ACV\n\nServed addressable market (SAM):\n- Ask: How many in markets you focus on?\n- Example: 100k SMB companies = £100M SAM\n\nYour market share:\n- If you have £5M ARR, and SAM £100M = 5% share\n- Benchmark: If competitors at 10-15%, you're behind\n- Growth: If gaining 1% share annually (growing 2x market), winning\n\nMarket size analysis:\n- Large TAM (£10B+): Can grow to £100M+ (attractive)\n- Small TAM (£100M): Likely max £10M (limited)\n- Shrinking market: Avoid (race to zero)\n- Growing market: Better (tailwinds)\n\n**Win/Loss Analysis**\n\nTrack why you win/lose deals to competitors:\n\nWins vs. Salesforce:\n- Reason 1: Price (we're 30% cheaper) - 40% of wins\n- Reason 2: Ease-of-use (we're simpler) - 30% of wins\n- Reason 3: Feature X (we have it, they don't) - 20% of wins\n- Other - 10%\n\nLosses to Salesforce:\n- Reason 1: Enterprise customers want Salesforce brand - 50% of losses\n- Reason 2: They need integration X (Salesforce has, we don't) - 30% of losses\n- Reason 3: Price (they chose cheaper alternative) - 10%\n- Other - 10%\n\nImplications:\n- Focus on what we win on (price, simplicity)\n- Don't fight on Salesforce's strength (brand, integrations)\n- Build missing integrations (quick win)\n- Double down on ease-of-use (core strength)\n\n**Monitoring Competitive Moves**\n\nStay informed:\n\n1. Subscribe to competitor emails (pricing changes?)\n2. Track G2, Capterra reviews (are they improving?)\n3. Monitor job postings (hiring for which markets?)\n4. Attend industry conferences (what are they announcing?)\n5. Talk to customers (what do competitors pitch?)\n6. LinkedIn follows (major announcements often there first)\n\nRed flags:\n- Competitor lowering price 50% (they're desperate or have new model)\n- Competitor hiring 50 salespeople (aggressive expansion coming)\n- Competitor launching new product (new market segment)\n- Competitor raises £100M (need to accelerate)\n\nResponse:\n- Don't panic (react thoughtfully, not emotionally)\n- Evaluate: Is this threat real?\n- Plan: What's our response (product? pricing? GTM?)\n- Execute: Implement response over weeks, not hours"
