        heading: "Building Growth into Your Product and Channels",
        body: "**Viral Coefficient Explained**\n\nFormula: K = (# invites sent per customer) × (% who accept invite and convert)\n\nExample:\n- 100 customers\n- Average: Each customer invites 5 people (collaboration product = natural invites)\n- Conversion: 40% of invitees convert to paid\n- K = 5 × 0.4 = 2.0 (2 new customers per existing customer)\n\nInterpretation:\n- K > 1: Viral (exponential growth, doubling rate)\n- K = 1: Breakeven (sustainable growth, no decay)\n- 0.5 < K < 1: Pseudo-viral (sustained growth, not exponential)\n- K < 0.3: Non-viral (must rely on marketing)\n\nGrowth impact:\n- K = 2.0 (viral): Double every month (2x month 1, 4x month 2, 8x month 3)\n- K = 0.2 (non-viral): Grow 20% per cohort (need constant marketing spend)\n\nExample:\n- Start: 100 customers\n- Month 1: Acquire 20 new, viral brings 20 × 2.0 = 40 from K = 60 new = 160 total\n- Month 2: Acquire 20 new, viral brings 160 × 2.0 = 320 from K = 340 new = 500 total\n- Month 3: 500 → 1500 (exponential)\n\nVs non-viral:\n- Start: 100 customers\n- Month 1: Acquire 20 new (must spend on marketing), viral brings 20 × 0.2 = 4 = 24 new = 124 total\n- Month 2: Acquire 20 new, viral brings 124 × 0.2 = 25 = 45 new = 169 total\n- Month 3: Acquire 20 new, viral brings 169 × 0.2 = 34 = 54 new = 223 total\n\nWhy viral is powerful:\n- Month 3: Viral at 1500, non-viral at 223 (6.7x difference)\n- Viral scales without increasing CAC\n- Non-viral requires constant marketing spend\n\n**Increasing Viral Coefficient**\n\nTactics:\n\n1. Improve NPS (happy customers refer more)\n   - NPS 70 customers refer 2x more than NPS 30\n   - Action: Fix product issues, improve onboarding\n\n2. Make product shareable\n   - Example: Figma (easy to share files, collaborators invited automatically)\n   - Example: Notion (shareable pages, comment to invite)\n   - Non-shareable: ERPsystem (not designed for sharing)\n   - Action: Build sharing into core workflow\n\n3. Add referral incentive\n   - Example: Dropbox (£2.5 credit per referral = drove huge growth)\n   - Example: Slack (£100 credit for referring team = viral loop)\n   - How much: £50-500 depending on ACV\n   - Action: Measure K with/without incentive\n\n4. Network effects (multi-user required)\n   - If product more valuable with more users, K naturally higher\n   - Example: Slack (solo user = useless, team of 10 = essential)\n   - Example: Zoom (works alone, but designed for meetings = network effect)\n   - Action: Require network (invite minimum 3 teammates) to get value\n\n5. Gamification\n   - Example: Leaderboards, badges (social sharing = bragging rights)\n   - Example: Streak tracking (share progress = social sharing)\n   - Action: Build social sharing into game mechanic\n\n**Product-Led Growth (PLG)**\n\nModel: Free product → customer self-discovers value → converts to paid\n\nExample (Figma):\n- Step 1: Sign up free (no credit card needed)\n- Step 2: Create file (intuitive design, quick aha moment)\n- Step 3: Invite collaborators (free accounts for teammates)\n- Step 4: Hit free limit (3 projects max, upgrade to unlock)\n- Step 5: Convert to paid (team growth = need more projects)\n\nPLG metrics:\n- Free sign-ups: 10,000/month\n- Trial-to-paid conversion: 5% = 500 new customers\n- CAC: Effectively £0 (product is marketing)\n- LTV: High (network effects, collaborators = stickier)\n\nWhy PLG works:\n- Low friction (try before buying)\n- Self-service (no sales call needed)\n- Network effects (teammates = users)\n- NPS naturally high (customers choose you, not sold to)\n\nDownside:\n- Conversion usually 2-5% (not all free users convert)\n- Requires intuitive product (can't rely on support to educate)\n- CAC low but also LTV lower (free users don't care about product quality)\n\n**Network Effects and Growth**\n\nNetwork effect: More users = more valuable\n\nExample:\n- 1 user on Slack: Useless (no one to chat with)\n- 10 users: Valuable (team collaboration)\n- 100 users: Very valuable (org-wide communication)\n- Value increases non-linearly (each new user adds more value)\n\nNetwork effect businesses:\n- Slack (collaboration = exponential value)\n- LinkedIn (connections = exponential value)\n- Zoom (conference calls = network effect)\n- Figma (collaboration = network effect)\n\nNon-network effect businesses:\n- Password manager (1 user = full value, 100 users = same value per user)\n- Billing software (1 company = full value, 100 companies = same value per user)\n- Email client (1 user = full value, 100 users = same value per user)\n\nWhy it matters for growth:\n- Network effect products: Grow faster once critical mass reached (flywheel)\n- Non-network effect: Must rely on marketing (no flywheel)\n\nBootstrapping with network effects:\n- Chicken-and-egg problem: Need users to create value, need value to attract users\n- Solution: Seed the network\n  - Example: LinkedIn started with famous investors, attracted others\n  - Example: Slack started with high-profile customers, grew from there\n  - Example: Figma seeded with design community\n\n**Growth Loops vs. Campaigns**\n\nCampaign (one-time):\n- Example: \"Launch in ProductHunt\", get 1000 signups, grow 5% that week\n- Sustains for: 1-2 weeks\n- Effort: 1-2 months of prep\n- ROI: High short-term, zero long-term\n\nGrowth loop (recurring):\n- Example: \"Referral program\", each customer brings 0.2 new customers\n- Sustains for: Indefinitely (compound growth)\n- Effort: 2-3 weeks to implement\n- ROI: Low short-term, exponential long-term\n\nBest: Combine (campaigns + loops)\n- Use campaign to bootstrap\n- Build loop to sustain\n- Example: ProductHunt launch (campaign) + referral loop (sustain)\n\n**Measuring Product-Led Growth**\n\nKey metrics:\n\n1. Viral coefficient (K)\n   - Target: >0.3 (baseline sustainable), >0.5 (strong), >1.0 (exponential)\n   - How: Track referral source (\"How did you hear about us?\"), calculate conversion\n\n2. Activation rate (% who reach aha moment)\n   - Target: 70%+ (strong product)\n   - How: Track aha metrics (first project created, invite sent, etc)\n\n3. Free-to-paid conversion\n   - Target: 2-5% (typical)\n   - How: Divide paid signups / free signups\n\n4. Product-qualified lead (PQL)\n   - Definition: Free user who shows high engagement = likely to convert\n   - Example: Created 5+ projects, invited 3+ collaborators = high PQL\n   - Action: Email high-PQL users about premium features\n\n5. Payback period from product\n   - Example: CAC £0 (product is marketing), LTV £1500 = payback immediate\n   - Compare to sales model: CAC £5000, LTV £15000, payback 3 months\n   - PLG usually better payback"
